WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.450 --> 00:00:04.635
Prof: Let us begin then
with the subject of today,

00:00:04.635 --> 00:00:05.830
which is the fugue.
 

00:00:05.830 --> 00:00:10.150
Every educated person should
know what a fugue is.

00:00:10.150 --> 00:00:10.680
Why?
 

00:00:10.680 --> 00:00:15.981
Because it's an intellectual
model, an intellectual paradigm

00:00:15.981 --> 00:00:20.743
that surfaces in a number of
disciplines--for example,

00:00:20.743 --> 00:00:22.630
in poetry, oddly.
 

00:00:22.630 --> 00:00:26.898
If you've ever peeked at
Thomas--T.S. Eliot's "The

00:00:26.898 --> 00:00:30.772
Four Quartets,"
the structure of the fugue is

00:00:30.772 --> 00:00:33.460
referenced there frequently.
 

00:00:33.460 --> 00:00:36.082
We could go to literature--a
novel written about the same

00:00:36.082 --> 00:00:38.470
time, Aldous Huxley's Point
Counter Point.

00:00:38.470 --> 00:00:41.960
It's framed in the shape of a
fugue.

00:00:41.960 --> 00:00:44.340
We could go to geology.
 

00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:47.789
Geologists occasionally will
say, "This particular

00:00:47.789 --> 00:00:50.920
crystal has a fugue-like
structure to it."

00:00:50.920 --> 00:00:53.038
Turning to painting,
there are painters of the

00:00:53.038 --> 00:00:53.980
twentieth century.
 

00:00:53.980 --> 00:00:56.629
I can name at least three,
Franz Kupka,

00:00:56.629 --> 00:00:58.790
Henry Valensi,
and Josef Albers,

00:00:58.790 --> 00:01:02.695
who used to be the dean of our
own Yale School of Art and

00:01:02.695 --> 00:01:04.019
Architecture.
 

00:01:04.019 --> 00:01:08.326
They all painted fugues and we
will be looking at Alber's

00:01:08.326 --> 00:01:10.504
fugue--
which actually happens to be in

00:01:10.504 --> 00:01:12.831
your textbook--
when we come to section this

00:01:12.831 --> 00:01:16.180
week, so be sure to bring your
textbooks to section this week

00:01:16.180 --> 00:01:20.110
'cause we'll--
we will be using them.

00:01:20.110 --> 00:01:23.552
I'm interested in the fugue
also because of this book,

00:01:23.552 --> 00:01:26.540
Douglas Hofstadter's Godel,
Escher, Bach.

00:01:26.540 --> 00:01:28.390
Oh, my. That's heavy.
 

00:01:28.390 --> 00:01:30.188
My--mine--I didn't bring in my
copy.

00:01:30.188 --> 00:01:32.638
This is the Bass copy that
Lynda was kind enough to pull

00:01:32.638 --> 00:01:32.950
over.
 

00:01:32.950 --> 00:01:34.430
Mine is a paperback.
 

00:01:34.430 --> 00:01:36.933
It's not this heavy,
but in a way this is

00:01:36.933 --> 00:01:39.500
indicative, because it's heavy
reading.

00:01:39.500 --> 00:01:42.480
Anybody ever peeked at this
book and any other--good.

00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:43.660
Is it Adam?
 

00:01:43.660 --> 00:01:44.090
Student: Yeah.
 

00:01:44.090 --> 00:01:45.101
Prof: Yeah.
 

00:01:45.101 --> 00:01:47.349
Adam, what course did you read
this in?

00:01:47.349 --> 00:01:49.560
Student: It was
recommended by a friend.

00:01:49.560 --> 00:01:50.780
Prof: Recommended by a
friend.

00:01:50.780 --> 00:01:53.135
I can follow about the first
twenty-five or thirty pages or

00:01:53.135 --> 00:01:53.340
so.
 

00:01:53.340 --> 00:01:56.940
Then when it gets to the math
it really gets over my head,

00:01:56.940 --> 00:02:00.811
but what it is is an attempt to
use the fugue as a way of

00:02:00.811 --> 00:02:04.408
bringing a common mode of
understanding to the visual

00:02:04.408 --> 00:02:07.129
arts,
to mathematics and to music.

00:02:07.129 --> 00:02:10.107
The musician that is
foregrounded here,

00:02:10.107 --> 00:02:14.258
of course, is J.S. Bach,
the master of the fugue.

00:02:14.258 --> 00:02:16.760
So we want to know about how
fugues operate,

00:02:16.760 --> 00:02:19.378
so let's take a look at the
specifics here.

00:02:19.378 --> 00:02:22.325
The term "fugue"
actually comes from an old

00:02:22.325 --> 00:02:24.147
Latin word,
"fuga,"

00:02:24.147 --> 00:02:27.293
which means "flight"
or "to fly,"

00:02:27.293 --> 00:02:30.680
so in a fugue what you get is
one voice going ahead,

00:02:30.680 --> 00:02:33.758
leading ahead,
and another voice following it.

00:02:33.758 --> 00:02:36.009
Now I just used the term
"voice"

00:02:36.009 --> 00:02:36.449
there.
 

00:02:36.449 --> 00:02:41.395
Fugues can be written for
actual voices sounding voices or

00:02:41.395 --> 00:02:45.992
they can be written for
instruments such as the violin

00:02:45.992 --> 00:02:49.030
or the cello--individual lines.
 

00:02:49.030 --> 00:02:51.995
They can even be written for
instruments that can play

00:02:51.995 --> 00:02:54.289
several lines or several parts
at once.

00:02:54.289 --> 00:02:55.110
The piano can do that.
 

00:02:55.110 --> 00:02:56.060
The organ can do that.
 

00:02:56.060 --> 00:02:58.538
Even the guitar and
occasionally the violin will be

00:02:58.538 --> 00:02:59.479
asked to do that.
 

00:02:59.479 --> 00:03:04.919
Fugues have been written for as
few as two voices.

00:03:04.919 --> 00:03:06.968
Yes, you could have a two-voice
fugue--

00:03:06.968 --> 00:03:10.288
up to as many as thirty-two
voices--

00:03:10.288 --> 00:03:16.103
and they can be,
as mentioned,

00:03:16.103 --> 00:03:20.485
written for--
and they are best,

00:03:20.485 --> 00:03:24.276
perhaps, performed on--
these keyboard instruments that

00:03:24.276 --> 00:03:26.740
have the capacity to play many
lines,

00:03:26.740 --> 00:03:28.620
many parts, many voices at once.
 

00:03:28.620 --> 00:03:30.770
The greatest collection of
fugues,

00:03:30.770 --> 00:03:35.032
that you may have bumped into,
heard about or at least heard

00:03:35.032 --> 00:03:37.348
the term,
is this collection of preludes

00:03:37.348 --> 00:03:39.911
and fugues by J.S. Bach called
"The Well-Tempered

00:03:39.911 --> 00:03:40.830
Clavier."
 

00:03:40.830 --> 00:03:42.120
First of all, what's a prelude?
 

00:03:42.120 --> 00:03:47.259
It's just a warm-up piece,
&gt;

00:03:47.259 --> 00:03:49.340
to just sort of get relaxed.
 

00:03:49.340 --> 00:03:51.548
You get to see your fingers,
get a feel of the keyboard or

00:03:51.548 --> 00:03:53.027
the--
of the lute or whatever it

00:03:53.027 --> 00:03:55.899
might happen to may be--
a prelude, a pre play,

00:03:55.899 --> 00:04:00.250
a warm-up, and then we go on to
the meat of the issue,

00:04:00.250 --> 00:04:02.408
which is the fugue.
 

00:04:02.408 --> 00:04:05.471
Now why is this called
"The Well-Tempered

00:04:05.471 --> 00:04:06.560
Clavier"?
 

00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:07.580
Anybody know?
 

00:04:07.580 --> 00:04:09.430
Anybody have--that's an odd
term.

00:04:09.430 --> 00:04:10.488
"Clavier"
just means

00:04:10.488 --> 00:04:11.766
"keyboard,"
the well-tuned

00:04:11.766 --> 00:04:12.680
"keyboard."
 

00:04:12.680 --> 00:04:14.840
Thoughts there?
 

00:04:14.840 --> 00:04:17.690
Well, what was going on in
Bach's day is that they didn't

00:04:17.690 --> 00:04:20.339
have a keyboard that--
&gt;

00:04:20.339 --> 00:04:23.466
they didn't have a tuning
system in which all of the

00:04:23.466 --> 00:04:25.980
pitches were exactly a half step
apart.

00:04:25.980 --> 00:04:27.800
Some were slightly
&gt;

00:04:27.800 --> 00:04:30.699
closer together,
and then others farther apart.

00:04:30.699 --> 00:04:32.519
And the key of &lt;&lt;plays
piano&gt;&gt;

00:04:32.519 --> 00:04:35.199
C actually had a slightly
different sound than the key of

00:04:35.199 --> 00:04:36.730
D, &gt;
 

00:04:36.730 --> 00:04:40.430
and it's only in the eighteenth
and nineteenth century that we

00:04:40.430 --> 00:04:43.766
gradually shifted from an
unequal keyboard to an equally

00:04:43.766 --> 00:04:44.920
tuned keyboard.
 

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:49.576
So Bach is kind of part of this
transition to the equal-tuned

00:04:49.576 --> 00:04:50.430
keyboard.
 

00:04:50.430 --> 00:04:54.461
He was getting close to the
equal temperament of the modern

00:04:54.461 --> 00:04:57.935
keyboard and that's why he
called it the well-tuned

00:04:57.935 --> 00:05:01.310
keyboard,
and it--by tuning it this way,

00:05:01.310 --> 00:05:04.509
it allows you to modulate to
all keys,

00:05:04.509 --> 00:05:06.079
and that's what he did in this
collection.

00:05:06.079 --> 00:05:09.882
He wrote a--two books,
one in seventeen- about 1722,

00:05:09.882 --> 00:05:13.536
when he was in CÃ¶then and
another about 1742,

00:05:13.536 --> 00:05:15.550
when he was in Leipzig.
 

00:05:15.550 --> 00:05:19.113
And in each of these books we
have a total of twenty-four

00:05:19.113 --> 00:05:22.360
preludes and fugues:
one, the prelude and fugue in C

00:05:22.360 --> 00:05:24.778
major, &lt;&lt;plays
piano&gt;&gt;

00:05:24.778 --> 00:05:26.793
one prelude and fugue in C
minor, &lt;&lt;plays

00:05:26.793 --> 00:05:27.449
piano&gt;&gt;
 

00:05:27.449 --> 00:05:29.939
one prelude and fugue in
C-sharp major,

00:05:29.939 --> 00:05:31.839
&gt;
 

00:05:31.839 --> 00:05:33.937
and one prelude and fugue in
C-sharp minor &lt;&lt;plays

00:05:33.937 --> 00:05:34.509
piano&gt;&gt;
 

00:05:34.509 --> 00:05:36.781
and so on it goes,
all the way up the keyboard in

00:05:36.781 --> 00:05:38.440
that fashion--two books of
those.

00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:41.346
And this is kind of standard
fodder for those that want to

00:05:41.346 --> 00:05:42.980
become professional musicians.
 

00:05:42.980 --> 00:05:43.552
Okay.
 

00:05:43.552 --> 00:05:49.511
So that's what that is about,
"The Well-Tempered

00:05:49.511 --> 00:05:51.459
Clavier."
 

00:05:51.459 --> 00:05:54.627
We've been referencing Bach
here and nobody,

00:05:54.627 --> 00:05:58.310
of course, wrote better fugues
than J.S. Bach.

00:05:58.310 --> 00:05:59.670
Some continued.
 

00:05:59.670 --> 00:06:02.100
Some continued to write fugues.
 

00:06:02.100 --> 00:06:04.220
Mozart wrote some fugues,
Haydn wrote some fugues,

00:06:04.220 --> 00:06:06.088
Beethoven wrote some fugues and
so on,

00:06:06.088 --> 00:06:09.690
and even into the twentieth
century we have a few composers:

00:06:09.690 --> 00:06:12.007
Paul Hindemith,
used to teach at Yale,

00:06:12.007 --> 00:06:13.170
Dmitri Shostakovich.
 

00:06:13.170 --> 00:06:16.180
They wrote fugues,
but generally speaking the

00:06:16.180 --> 00:06:19.329
fugue has its heyday in the
Baroque period,

00:06:19.329 --> 00:06:22.939
roughly sixteen hundred to
seventeen fifty,

00:06:22.939 --> 00:06:25.569
the heyday of Bach and Handel.
 

00:06:25.569 --> 00:06:27.420
How do fugues work?
 

00:06:27.420 --> 00:06:31.024
Well, they start out--as
mentioned--with one voice

00:06:31.024 --> 00:06:35.216
leading forward and then another
voice imitates that voice

00:06:35.216 --> 00:06:36.100
exactly.
 

00:06:36.100 --> 00:06:38.790
Now if that following
voice--here's a question.

00:06:38.790 --> 00:06:42.060
If that following voice
imitated the leader exactly from

00:06:42.060 --> 00:06:44.379
beginning to end,
what would we have?

00:06:44.379 --> 00:06:47.269
Hm?
 

00:06:47.269 --> 00:06:48.600
Student: A round.
 

00:06:48.600 --> 00:06:50.240
Prof: A round.
 

00:06:50.240 --> 00:06:50.632
Okay.
 

00:06:50.632 --> 00:06:51.180
Good.
 

00:06:51.180 --> 00:06:52.540
That's what we would have,
a round.

00:06:52.540 --> 00:06:55.379
Or we could call--use the
fancier music word,

00:06:55.379 --> 00:06:56.800
a "canon."
 

00:06:56.800 --> 00:06:59.589
Canon, round--the same thing,
one voice imitating the other

00:06:59.589 --> 00:07:01.129
exactly from beginning to end.
 

00:07:01.129 --> 00:07:05.300
But in a fugue what happens is
after the main idea--

00:07:05.300 --> 00:07:07.009
which we'll be calling the
"subject"--

00:07:07.009 --> 00:07:10.738
the main idea is stated,
then the parts go their

00:07:10.738 --> 00:07:14.230
independent ways generating
counterpoint,

00:07:14.230 --> 00:07:18.031
but they're not exact;
they're not precise

00:07:18.031 --> 00:07:21.889
duplications of the rhythms and
the pitches of the leaders.

00:07:21.889 --> 00:07:26.045
So what we could do would be to
visualize this in a sort of

00:07:26.045 --> 00:07:27.480
crude way up here.
 

00:07:27.480 --> 00:07:29.980
We have a leader and then a
follower.

00:07:29.980 --> 00:07:33.033
And the follower duplicates the
main idea, which we're going to

00:07:33.033 --> 00:07:34.904
call the subject,
for a period of time,

00:07:34.904 --> 00:07:36.629
but then it kind of breaks off.
 

00:07:36.629 --> 00:07:40.105
So voices will come in and
duplicate a certain amount of

00:07:40.105 --> 00:07:43.329
material and then break off and
go their own way.

00:07:43.329 --> 00:07:46.803
So that's a good way of
thinking of the beginning of a

00:07:46.803 --> 00:07:50.410
fugue, which we will call the
"exposition."

00:07:50.410 --> 00:07:52.279
I'll come back to that point in
a moment.

00:07:52.279 --> 00:07:54.771
Notice here I've put a
little--silly little tree up

00:07:54.771 --> 00:07:55.120
here.
 

00:07:55.120 --> 00:07:58.389
We could say that we have the
genus polyphony here and we've

00:07:58.389 --> 00:08:00.884
got monophonic texture,
homophonic texture and

00:08:00.884 --> 00:08:02.160
polyphonic texture.
 

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:06.562
So within polyphonic texture we
have non-imitative texture and

00:08:06.562 --> 00:08:10.675
then a stream of imitative
polyphony and then two forms of

00:08:10.675 --> 00:08:13.887
imitative polyphony,
rather strict--exactly

00:08:13.887 --> 00:08:17.413
strict--imitative polyphony,
the canon, and less strict

00:08:17.413 --> 00:08:19.800
imitative polyphony--
the fugue.

00:08:19.800 --> 00:08:20.425
Okay?
 

00:08:20.425 --> 00:08:24.050
Questions about that so far?
 

00:08:24.050 --> 00:08:24.654
All right.
 

00:08:24.654 --> 00:08:27.379
Let's go back to the beginning
of the fugue.

00:08:27.379 --> 00:08:30.302
We have this opening melody,
the distinctive part of it,

00:08:30.302 --> 00:08:32.428
which we're going to call the
subject.

00:08:32.428 --> 00:08:34.615
That's just what we call the
melody in a fugue,

00:08:34.615 --> 00:08:35.279
the subject.
 

00:08:35.279 --> 00:08:39.730
And the way this works is in a
fugue each of the voices in turn

00:08:39.730 --> 00:08:42.100
will come in with that subject.
 

00:08:42.100 --> 00:08:44.504
One will start out,
then another will come in,

00:08:44.504 --> 00:08:46.000
then another will come in.
 

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:49.871
After all of the voices are in,
we're at the end of what we

00:08:49.871 --> 00:08:52.210
call the exposition of the
fugue.

00:08:52.210 --> 00:08:54.602
Now we have had the term
"exposition"

00:08:54.602 --> 00:08:56.058
before and where was that?
 

00:08:56.058 --> 00:08:57.210
Student:
&gt;

00:08:57.210 --> 00:08:59.792
Prof: Over there,
Elizabeth.

00:08:59.792 --> 00:09:00.779
I hear you.
 

00:09:00.779 --> 00:09:01.720
Student: --sonata form?
 

00:09:01.720 --> 00:09:03.423
Prof: Yeah,
sonata form,

00:09:03.423 --> 00:09:06.206
sonata-allegro form,
so we--and what do we mean by

00:09:06.206 --> 00:09:08.080
"exposition"
there?

00:09:08.080 --> 00:09:10.241
Well, it's a chance where you
present all of the--all the

00:09:10.241 --> 00:09:12.327
themes, and we talked about
first theme and then second

00:09:12.327 --> 00:09:13.408
theme and closing theme.
 

00:09:13.408 --> 00:09:16.774
Well, here in a fugue we have
just one theme but everybody's

00:09:16.774 --> 00:09:19.000
going to get a chance to present
it,

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:20.798
and after everyone has a chance
to present it--

00:09:20.798 --> 00:09:22.408
every voice has a chance to
present it--

00:09:22.408 --> 00:09:25.000
then we're finished with the
exposition;

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:28.389
all the voices have exposed the
theme in their range.

00:09:28.389 --> 00:09:32.115
After that we go to what's
called the "episode"

00:09:32.115 --> 00:09:32.980
of a fugue.
 

00:09:32.980 --> 00:09:34.538
What happens in an episode?
 

00:09:34.538 --> 00:09:38.283
Well, usually it modulates key
and the vehicle through

00:09:38.283 --> 00:09:41.745
composers frequently modulate is
melodic sequence,

00:09:41.745 --> 00:09:43.298
either up or down.
 

00:09:43.298 --> 00:09:45.798
You can kind of move around by
using sequence.

00:09:45.798 --> 00:09:48.200
You can get to different places
by using sequence.

00:09:48.200 --> 00:09:52.517
So it tends to be contrapuntal
because it's using little

00:09:52.517 --> 00:09:54.480
motives from the theme.
 

00:09:54.480 --> 00:09:56.143
It modulates,
moves around a lot,

00:09:56.143 --> 00:09:58.690
goes to different keys,
sounds a bit unsettled.

00:09:58.690 --> 00:10:02.996
If you were to think back on
sonata-allegro form and try to

00:10:02.996 --> 00:10:06.711
find an analog for
sonata-allegro form in the fugue

00:10:06.711 --> 00:10:08.940
episode, what would it be?
 

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:12.789
What is the episode of the
fugue like in sonata-allegro

00:10:12.789 --> 00:10:13.289
form?
 

00:10:13.289 --> 00:10:14.059
Roger.
 

00:10:14.059 --> 00:10:14.950
Student: The development?
 

00:10:14.950 --> 00:10:16.960
Prof: Exactly--the
development section.

00:10:16.960 --> 00:10:20.221
So these episodes in a fugue
are sort of mini development

00:10:20.221 --> 00:10:22.615
sections,
so visualize if you will--we've

00:10:22.615 --> 00:10:24.750
started out here with the
exposition,

00:10:24.750 --> 00:10:27.220
in which all voices present the
subject.

00:10:27.220 --> 00:10:30.549
Then you have this kind of free
period in which the motive out

00:10:30.549 --> 00:10:33.498
of the subject is played with,
developed, moved around,

00:10:33.498 --> 00:10:34.700
different pitches.
 

00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:38.113
Then the subject will come back
in a new key because we've

00:10:38.113 --> 00:10:41.775
modulated in the episode,
subject in just one voice,

00:10:41.775 --> 00:10:43.984
new key,
then another episode in which

00:10:43.984 --> 00:10:46.099
there's modulation,
more counterpoint,

00:10:46.099 --> 00:10:48.491
more movement;
another statement of the

00:10:48.491 --> 00:10:51.788
subject in a new key;
another episode;

00:10:51.788 --> 00:10:54.330
another statement of the
subject, and on it goes until--

00:10:54.330 --> 00:10:56.750
oh, we run out of energy
usually about--

00:10:56.750 --> 00:11:00.264
after four or five minutes or
so, at which point the composer

00:11:00.264 --> 00:11:03.912
will bring the subject back--
maybe in the bass or in the

00:11:03.912 --> 00:11:07.509
soprano in a very prominent
range in the tonic key--

00:11:07.509 --> 00:11:08.580
and we have the sense,
"oh,

00:11:08.580 --> 00:11:12.620
this is a very solid moment;
yes, this fugue is ending."

00:11:12.620 --> 00:11:15.768
And maybe they'll throw upon
one or--throw one or two chords

00:11:15.768 --> 00:11:17.210
on the end but that's it.
 

00:11:17.210 --> 00:11:21.788
So it's a complex form,
but maybe not quite as complex

00:11:21.788 --> 00:11:23.950
as sonata-allegro form.
 

00:11:23.950 --> 00:11:26.590
What's a definition then?
 

00:11:26.590 --> 00:11:29.750
If you're taking notes there,
what's a definition of a fugue?

00:11:29.750 --> 00:11:33.020
Well, I wrote a definition of a
fugue and I will read the

00:11:33.020 --> 00:11:34.950
definition out of the textbook.
 

00:11:34.950 --> 00:11:37.667
Students don't like this,
I've found, if you read out of

00:11:37.667 --> 00:11:38.308
a textbook.
 

00:11:38.308 --> 00:11:42.053
But I ought to be able to do
this since I wrote the textbook.

00:11:42.053 --> 00:11:42.490
Okay?
 

00:11:42.490 --> 00:11:45.950
So I'm going to read a good
definition of a fugue here.

00:11:45.950 --> 00:11:50.418
Definition of the fugue:
A composition for two,

00:11:50.418 --> 00:11:55.139
three or four parts played or
sung by voices or instruments

00:11:55.139 --> 00:12:00.019
which begins with a presentation
of a subject in imitation in

00:12:00.019 --> 00:12:01.159
each part.
 

00:12:01.159 --> 00:12:02.278
The episode--excuse me.
 

00:12:02.278 --> 00:12:05.990
The exposition continues with
modulating passages of free

00:12:05.990 --> 00:12:08.706
counterpoint--
the episodes--and further

00:12:08.706 --> 00:12:12.013
appearances of the subject,
and ends with a strong

00:12:12.013 --> 00:12:13.899
affirmation of the tonic key.
 

00:12:13.899 --> 00:12:17.657
Well, you can't write all that
down, but if you want to just

00:12:17.657 --> 00:12:20.331
put in your notes:
For definition of fugue,

00:12:20.331 --> 00:12:22.178
see page 144 of the text.
 

00:12:22.178 --> 00:12:26.414
Fortunately,
as I say, it's easier to hear

00:12:26.414 --> 00:12:31.269
and look at fugues than it is to
define them.

00:12:31.269 --> 00:12:31.841
All right.
 

00:12:31.841 --> 00:12:34.649
Now today we're going to do
something different.

00:12:34.649 --> 00:12:37.796
It's the only day in our course
where we're actually going to

00:12:37.796 --> 00:12:38.529
look at music.
 

00:12:38.529 --> 00:12:38.950
Okay?
 

00:12:38.950 --> 00:12:42.186
We've handed out music for
you--an entire piece,

00:12:42.186 --> 00:12:45.352
an entire fugue by J.S. Bach
here, and ideally,

00:12:45.352 --> 00:12:49.484
I guess, we'd be in a seminar
format and we'd all be standing

00:12:49.484 --> 00:12:51.548
around the piano here.
 

00:12:51.548 --> 00:12:57.356
So my first question for you is
for how many voices is this

00:12:57.356 --> 00:12:58.960
fugue written?
 

00:12:58.960 --> 00:13:05.360
Look at just the first page and
look vertically and see what's

00:13:05.360 --> 00:13:11.760
the maximum number of pitches
you have sounding simultaneously

00:13:11.760 --> 00:13:14.070
at any one moment.
 

00:13:14.070 --> 00:13:20.750
Caroline, is it?
 

00:13:20.750 --> 00:13:21.649
Student: Three?
 

00:13:21.649 --> 00:13:22.669
Prof: Three. Okay?
 

00:13:22.669 --> 00:13:23.798
Yeah, we have three.
 

00:13:23.798 --> 00:13:26.172
If you look through,
there are--sometimes at the

00:13:26.172 --> 00:13:29.150
very beginning there's just one
voice and then there are two

00:13:29.150 --> 00:13:31.070
voices and then the three
voices,

00:13:31.070 --> 00:13:32.668
three lines.
 

00:13:32.668 --> 00:13:35.870
But it never gets to be more
than three lines.

00:13:35.870 --> 00:13:40.524
So we have our exposition here
and it consists of three

00:13:40.524 --> 00:13:42.940
statements of the subject.
 

00:13:42.940 --> 00:13:46.173
We're going to call these three
voices, or lines,

00:13:46.173 --> 00:13:48.798
the alto, &lt;&lt;plays
piano&gt;&gt;

00:13:48.798 --> 00:13:50.840
the soprano,
&gt;

00:13:50.840 --> 00:13:54.070
and the bass,
&gt;

00:13:54.070 --> 00:13:56.769
which comes in in bar seven
there.

00:13:56.769 --> 00:13:58.570
So here's a little bit of the
beginning of this.

00:13:58.570 --> 00:14:25.120
&gt;
 

00:14:25.120 --> 00:14:25.538
Okay.
 

00:14:25.538 --> 00:14:29.903
So that's our exposition,
because each of the voices,

00:14:29.903 --> 00:14:34.268
alto, soprano and bass,
has come in and presented the

00:14:34.268 --> 00:14:35.360
subject.
 

00:14:35.360 --> 00:14:38.110
Now we have bars nine and ten
here.

00:14:38.110 --> 00:14:45.320
&gt;
 

00:14:45.320 --> 00:14:56.399
What's that if I just go
&gt;?

00:14:56.399 --> 00:14:57.830
Jerry, what's that?
 

00:14:57.830 --> 00:14:58.070
Student:
&gt;

00:14:58.070 --> 00:15:01.044
Prof: It's a melodic
sequence, and which direction is

00:15:01.044 --> 00:15:01.600
it going?
 

00:15:01.600 --> 00:15:02.418
Up or down?
 

00:15:02.418 --> 00:15:06.669
Well, that's maybe harder than
you think.

00:15:06.669 --> 00:15:15.028
&gt;
 

00:15:15.028 --> 00:15:18.581
Generally going down,
not because the line is going

00:15:18.581 --> 00:15:22.418
down, but we're starting
&gt;

00:15:22.418 --> 00:15:27.864
each time on a successively
lower pitch, and this sequence

00:15:27.864 --> 00:15:31.590
takes us &lt;&lt;plays
piano&gt;&gt;.

00:15:31.590 --> 00:15:36.871
So we've started in this kind
of tonality &lt;&lt;plays

00:15:36.871 --> 00:15:38.340
piano&gt;&gt;
 

00:15:38.340 --> 00:15:41.514
which is minor,
but now by the time we've

00:15:41.514 --> 00:15:45.799
gotten to bar ten and eleven
particularly &lt;&lt;plays

00:15:45.799 --> 00:15:47.149
piano&gt;&gt;
 

00:15:47.149 --> 00:15:48.970
he's modulated.
 

00:15:48.970 --> 00:15:52.740
So that's what our little
episode was in bars nine and ten

00:15:52.740 --> 00:15:53.269
there.
 

00:15:53.269 --> 00:15:56.480
It allowed us to move from a
minor key to a major key.

00:15:56.480 --> 00:15:59.875
And now the subject comes back
in and, as you can see,

00:15:59.875 --> 00:16:01.668
what voice is it in there?
 

00:16:01.668 --> 00:16:07.110
What voice is the subject in
bar eleven?

00:16:07.110 --> 00:16:08.190
Pretty straightforward.
 

00:16:08.190 --> 00:16:10.289
Somebody yell it out.
 

00:16:10.289 --> 00:16:10.970
Student: Soprano.
 

00:16:10.970 --> 00:16:11.951
Prof: Soprano.
 

00:16:11.951 --> 00:16:13.820
Okay, so here--heads up on the
soprano.

00:16:13.820 --> 00:16:21.350
&gt;
 

00:16:21.350 --> 00:16:24.926
So there we are,
a nice statement of the theme

00:16:24.926 --> 00:16:27.309
in the major in the soprano.
 

00:16:27.309 --> 00:16:34.840
&gt;
 

00:16:34.840 --> 00:16:37.678
What happened in that little
episode?

00:16:37.678 --> 00:16:40.168
We were here &lt;&lt;plays
piano&gt;&gt;

00:16:40.168 --> 00:16:42.509
and now we're here,
&gt;

00:16:42.509 --> 00:16:48.467
modulated again to minor,
and there in bar fifteen,

00:16:48.467 --> 00:16:51.210
where is the subject?
 

00:16:51.210 --> 00:17:00.769
&gt;
 

00:17:00.769 --> 00:17:02.710
Which bar?
 

00:17:02.710 --> 00:17:04.569
Chris.
 

00:17:04.569 --> 00:17:05.098
Student: Alto?
 

00:17:05.098 --> 00:17:05.920
Prof: Alto part.
 

00:17:05.920 --> 00:17:06.097
Good.
 

00:17:06.097 --> 00:17:06.420
Thanks.
 

00:17:06.420 --> 00:17:07.730
So there it is in the alto part.
 

00:17:07.730 --> 00:17:10.682
That's an interesting moment
there because we've got a

00:17:10.682 --> 00:17:13.191
three-voice fugue,
and how many hands does the

00:17:13.191 --> 00:17:14.250
performer have?
 

00:17:14.250 --> 00:17:16.838
Obviously two,
so at some moments these hands

00:17:16.838 --> 00:17:20.369
are going to have to share a
subject, and that's what happens

00:17:20.369 --> 00:17:21.430
in that voice.
 

00:17:21.430 --> 00:17:24.713
When you play this--take a look
there, the very last measure of

00:17:24.713 --> 00:17:25.348
that page.
 

00:17:25.348 --> 00:17:26.045
It must be fifteen.
 

00:17:26.045 --> 00:17:27.068
&gt;
 

00:17:27.068 --> 00:17:32.054
It starts out--my left hand is
playing here &lt;&lt;plays

00:17:32.054 --> 00:17:33.390
piano&gt;&gt;
 

00:17:33.390 --> 00:17:36.277
and then the left hand has to
go down and pick up the

00:17:36.277 --> 00:17:39.498
counterpoint in the bass and the
right hand takes over that

00:17:39.498 --> 00:17:49.410
subject,
&gt;

00:17:49.410 --> 00:17:53.250
but it's the job of the pianist
there who--

00:17:53.250 --> 00:17:54.858
or the keyboardist,
whoever is playing it--

00:17:54.858 --> 00:17:58.122
to really lean on the inside of
your hand there because when

00:17:58.122 --> 00:18:00.390
you'd normally play these
instruments,

00:18:00.390 --> 00:18:02.509
there's a tendency--and I'm
sure Santana,

00:18:02.509 --> 00:18:04.210
who is a far better keyboardist
than I,

00:18:04.210 --> 00:18:07.308
will confirm this--there's a
tendency to roll to either side.

00:18:07.308 --> 00:18:09.028
It's easier to play bass and
soprano.

00:18:09.028 --> 00:18:12.605
What's hard to do is to get
those inner voices so the

00:18:12.605 --> 00:18:16.180
keyboard player has to
&gt;

00:18:16.180 --> 00:18:26.450
and then &lt;&lt;plays
piano&gt;&gt;

00:18:26.450 --> 00:18:27.798
so you can really hear that.
 

00:18:27.798 --> 00:18:29.972
If you didn't hear it,
then that wasn't a good

00:18:29.972 --> 00:18:30.650
performance.
 

00:18:30.650 --> 00:18:31.464
All right.
 

00:18:31.464 --> 00:18:34.808
Now that takes us across the
page there.

00:18:34.808 --> 00:18:36.269
We're now back in &lt;&lt;plays
piano&gt;&gt;

00:18:36.269 --> 00:18:37.868
a minor key.
 

00:18:37.868 --> 00:18:40.673
This is bar sixteen and
seventeen, and in bars

00:18:40.673 --> 00:18:43.541
seventeen, eighteen,
nineteen, the beginning of

00:18:43.541 --> 00:18:46.160
twenty, we have an interesting
moment.

00:18:46.160 --> 00:18:48.569
It's called invertible
counterpoint.

00:18:48.569 --> 00:18:50.009
What do we mean by that?
 

00:18:50.009 --> 00:18:57.568
Well, he has a motive
&gt;

00:18:57.568 --> 00:19:00.362
and we're going to call that
motive A, and he has another

00:19:00.362 --> 00:19:01.309
motive, motive B.
 

00:19:01.309 --> 00:19:05.440
&gt;
 

00:19:05.440 --> 00:19:09.653
So there is B in the alto,
A in the bass,

00:19:09.653 --> 00:19:13.972
and together they sound sort of
like this.

00:19:13.972 --> 00:19:17.240
&gt;
 

00:19:17.240 --> 00:19:18.549
Okay? Cool.
 

00:19:18.549 --> 00:19:20.819
Now the next three bars.
 

00:19:20.819 --> 00:19:21.730
What happens?
 

00:19:21.730 --> 00:19:27.160
Well, he takes B &lt;&lt;plays
piano&gt;&gt;

00:19:27.160 --> 00:19:31.420
and so he takes B and puts that
below A.

00:19:31.420 --> 00:19:33.269
He's switching the positions
here.

00:19:33.269 --> 00:19:38.180
A is now &lt;&lt;plays
piano&gt;&gt;.

00:19:38.180 --> 00:19:41.390
Both of these motives are
coming up in rising sequence.

00:19:41.390 --> 00:19:44.428
So let's go back to the
beginning of seventeen there and

00:19:44.428 --> 00:19:46.029
we'll listen to the switch.
 

00:19:46.029 --> 00:19:59.230
&gt;
 

00:19:59.230 --> 00:20:00.548
All right.
 

00:20:00.548 --> 00:20:03.305
So that goes by very quickly.
 

00:20:03.305 --> 00:20:03.970
Right?
 

00:20:03.970 --> 00:20:07.009
How long do you think it took
Bach to figure that out?

00:20:07.009 --> 00:20:07.826
I don't know.
 

00:20:07.826 --> 00:20:09.836
He's a very good
contrapuntalist,

00:20:09.836 --> 00:20:12.160
maybe "boom,"
like that.

00:20:12.160 --> 00:20:15.128
I'd have to sit there--Santana,
how long would it take you to

00:20:15.128 --> 00:20:17.751
figure out some invertible
counterpoint that you could

00:20:17.751 --> 00:20:20.155
think of one melody,
think up another melody that

00:20:20.155 --> 00:20:23.116
would be a harmony against it,
but yet you could flip the two

00:20:23.116 --> 00:20:25.450
and it would still sound pretty
darn good?

00:20:25.450 --> 00:20:27.759
It'd take a long time to kind
of work that out.

00:20:27.759 --> 00:20:29.880
So that's what's kind of neat
about fugue.

00:20:29.880 --> 00:20:33.227
There's all these intricacies
embedded in them that almost

00:20:33.227 --> 00:20:36.517
sail by the general listener
unless we happen to have the

00:20:36.517 --> 00:20:39.630
music right in front of us and
can dwell on them.

00:20:39.630 --> 00:20:40.214
All right.
 

00:20:40.214 --> 00:20:43.554
So that takes us over now to
bar twenty, where we are here

00:20:43.554 --> 00:20:46.190
back, I guess,
&gt;

00:20:46.190 --> 00:21:10.358
in our tonic key of C minor,
and the theme is up in the

00:21:10.358 --> 00:21:26.920
soprano &lt;&lt;plays
piano&gt;&gt;

00:21:26.920 --> 00:21:38.009
and then one final statement in
the soprano &lt;&lt;plays

00:21:38.009 --> 00:21:40.980
piano&gt;&gt;
 

00:21:40.980 --> 00:21:43.068
--a couple of interesting
points there.

00:21:43.068 --> 00:21:51.817
When we concluded this piece we
had this sound &lt;&lt;plays

00:21:51.817 --> 00:21:54.190
piano&gt;&gt;.
 

00:21:54.190 --> 00:21:56.798
What's a little bit surprising
about that?

00:21:56.798 --> 00:22:03.210
We're ending a piece that's
called the Fugue Number Two in C

00:22:03.210 --> 00:22:04.078
Minor.
 

00:22:04.078 --> 00:22:09.250
We are ending here with
&gt;.

00:22:09.250 --> 00:22:10.349
Does that sound like a minor
chord again?

00:22:10.349 --> 00:22:12.019
No, no. A major chord.
 

00:22:12.019 --> 00:22:13.538
All right. So he's changed it.
 

00:22:13.538 --> 00:22:16.265
This is a standard
gamut--gambit from the late

00:22:16.265 --> 00:22:20.019
sixteenth right through the
eighteenth century-- last chord.

00:22:20.019 --> 00:22:21.670
They didn't like to end pieces
in minor.

00:22:21.670 --> 00:22:22.930
Maybe it was too depressing or
whatever.

00:22:22.930 --> 00:22:25.470
&gt;
 

00:22:25.470 --> 00:22:30.451
Oh, don't want to do that,
so &gt;

00:22:30.451 --> 00:22:33.338
&gt;
 

00:22:33.338 --> 00:22:36.130
with the major third up there
above.

00:22:36.130 --> 00:22:38.798
That's called the Picardy
third, maybe from the Old French

00:22:38.798 --> 00:22:40.998
word picart,
which means sort of sharp or

00:22:40.998 --> 00:22:41.558
pointed.
 

00:22:41.558 --> 00:22:43.319
So we have a pointed ending
there.

00:22:43.319 --> 00:22:44.298
We have a major ending.
 

00:22:44.298 --> 00:22:47.766
Here's another issue when
we're--since we're on the topic

00:22:47.766 --> 00:22:50.490
of points and that's called a
pedal point.

00:22:50.490 --> 00:22:54.500
What was J.S. Bach known as
in his day?

00:22:54.500 --> 00:22:55.849
Was he known as a great
composer?

00:22:55.849 --> 00:22:58.009
What was he known as?
 

00:22:58.009 --> 00:23:00.049
How did he earn--basically,
how did he earn his living?

00:23:00.049 --> 00:23:02.587
Student: He played--
Prof: He played

00:23:02.587 --> 00:23:04.596
the--you're getting warm.
 

00:23:04.596 --> 00:23:05.160
Yeah?
 

00:23:05.160 --> 00:23:05.690
Student: Is it organ?
 

00:23:05.690 --> 00:23:07.019
Prof: He played the
organ.

00:23:07.019 --> 00:23:11.130
He was the great organ virtuoso
of his day, and I think at the

00:23:11.130 --> 00:23:14.769
end of this particular fugue
here, it's interesting.

00:23:14.769 --> 00:23:16.660
He just has this line sit there.
 

00:23:16.660 --> 00:23:23.130
&gt;
 

00:23:23.130 --> 00:23:23.453
Okay.
 

00:23:23.453 --> 00:23:27.542
On the organ that would just be
fine and dandy because you'd put

00:23:27.542 --> 00:23:31.113
your foot down there on that low
C &gt;

00:23:31.113 --> 00:23:33.190
&gt;
 

00:23:33.190 --> 00:23:35.368
and that tonic note would
continue to hold,

00:23:35.368 --> 00:23:38.268
but if you were writing this
for the clavichord or the

00:23:38.268 --> 00:23:41.377
harpsichord or the piano,
what happens to that sound once

00:23:41.377 --> 00:23:41.990
you hit it?
 

00:23:41.990 --> 00:23:43.500
It dies away.
 

00:23:43.500 --> 00:23:46.039
I think in the end of this
piece here Bach had the sound of

00:23:46.039 --> 00:23:46.608
the organ .
 

00:23:46.608 --> 00:23:48.200
He didn't really--he wasn't
thinking "gee,

00:23:48.200 --> 00:23:50.420
if this is really for a
harpsichord or something,

00:23:50.420 --> 00:23:58.404
I'd better write this like
this-- &lt;&lt;plays

00:23:58.404 --> 00:24:01.009
piano&gt;&gt;
 

00:24:01.009 --> 00:24:03.094
so we get a nice,
strong tonic sound at the

00:24:03.094 --> 00:24:03.690
end."
 

00:24:03.690 --> 00:24:07.618
He may have had the sound of
the organ there in his ear,

00:24:07.618 --> 00:24:10.862
but perhaps the important point
here is this idea of a pedal

00:24:10.862 --> 00:24:14.324
point 'cause we've actually even
talked about that before in the

00:24:14.324 --> 00:24:17.675
Johannes Brahms Variations on
a Theme of Haydn that was

00:24:17.675 --> 00:24:19.380
performed Saturday night.
 

00:24:19.380 --> 00:24:20.930
Pedal point is what?
 

00:24:20.930 --> 00:24:25.789
Anybody who can define pedal
point for us?

00:24:25.789 --> 00:24:27.259
Hm?
 

00:24:27.259 --> 00:24:28.077
Well, what goes on?
 

00:24:28.077 --> 00:24:28.940
It's pretty simple.
 

00:24:28.940 --> 00:24:30.730
Roger.
 

00:24:30.730 --> 00:24:34.038
Student: The bass holds
a note &gt;

00:24:34.038 --> 00:24:35.038
Prof: Yeah.
 

00:24:35.038 --> 00:24:38.035
The bass holds a note and
basically you're just kind of

00:24:38.035 --> 00:24:41.086
running over top of one,
possibly two harmonies up above

00:24:41.086 --> 00:24:43.140
it, but it all sounds consonant.
 

00:24:43.140 --> 00:24:46.648
So just be sure of the idea of
one note usually in the bass

00:24:46.648 --> 00:24:49.069
just holding,
holding, holding for a long

00:24:49.069 --> 00:24:50.220
period of time.
 

00:24:50.220 --> 00:24:55.710
 
 

00:24:55.710 --> 00:24:58.088
Okay.
 

00:24:58.088 --> 00:25:01.328
Any questions about that fugue
by J.S. Bach?

00:25:01.328 --> 00:25:03.349
Anybody want to ask anything
about that?

00:25:03.349 --> 00:25:07.640
 
 

00:25:07.640 --> 00:25:09.549
Marcus, that works for you?
 

00:25:09.549 --> 00:25:12.619
Ugonna, okay?
 

00:25:12.619 --> 00:25:15.039
Thaddeus, no questions?
 

00:25:15.039 --> 00:25:17.759
Frederick.
 

00:25:17.759 --> 00:25:21.039
Student: At the very end
that's a total of what?

00:25:21.039 --> 00:25:22.730
Four notes being played at once?
 

