Prof: Oh,
okay.

00:25:24.378 --> 00:25:24.770
Good.
 

00:25:24.770 --> 00:25:25.400
Yeah.
 

00:25:25.400 --> 00:25:26.380
Thanks for bringing that out.
 

00:25:26.380 --> 00:25:29.650
There at the end we could even
have--

00:25:29.650 --> 00:25:31.752
you're right--four,
maybe even five notes played at

00:25:31.752 --> 00:25:33.729
once,
so this idea that you--once you

00:25:33.729 --> 00:25:36.743
have three parts you can only
have three parts or once you

00:25:36.743 --> 00:25:39.242
have five-voice fugue,
you can have no more than five

00:25:39.242 --> 00:25:41.670
voices--
breaks down at the very end.

00:25:41.670 --> 00:25:44.655
Why would you imagine a
composer would want to do that,

00:25:44.655 --> 00:25:45.318
Frederick?
 

00:25:45.318 --> 00:25:46.769
Student:
&gt;

00:25:46.769 --> 00:25:48.588
pieces at one time.
 

00:25:48.588 --> 00:25:51.836
Prof: Well,
no, it's not that hard because

00:25:51.836 --> 00:25:53.371
you--
once you get used to the idea

00:25:53.371 --> 00:25:55.547
of a C major triad,
you--a musician would look at

00:25:55.547 --> 00:25:57.863
that end and say,
"I've just got a C major

00:25:57.863 --> 00:25:58.200
triad.
 

00:25:58.200 --> 00:25:59.470
I'm going to just bang down on
it."

00:25:59.470 --> 00:26:01.534
So that's not hard technically
or intellectually,

00:26:01.534 --> 00:26:03.942
but why would a--the--you
raised a very interesting point

00:26:03.942 --> 00:26:04.328
here.
 

00:26:04.328 --> 00:26:07.028
Why would a composer want to
add more notes at the end?

00:26:07.028 --> 00:26:08.579
I think it's a pretty
straightforward idea.

00:26:08.579 --> 00:26:12.000
David? Michael, yeah.
 

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:12.308
Student: They make it
louder.

00:26:12.308 --> 00:26:14.101
Prof: Yeah,
just make it louder,

00:26:14.101 --> 00:26:16.344
make it more sonorous,
a big bang ending sort of

00:26:16.344 --> 00:26:18.395
thing, yeah,
to tell the listener once again

00:26:18.395 --> 00:26:21.308
that this is something special
and we're probably at the end.

00:26:21.308 --> 00:26:21.904
All right.
 

00:26:21.904 --> 00:26:24.230
So let's listen to just a bit
of this.

00:26:24.230 --> 00:26:25.858
We had one version of this.
 

00:26:25.858 --> 00:26:29.769
Let's listen to a contemporary
