00:29:15.298 --> 00:29:17.628
It's a plucked,
a pizzicato double bass,

00:29:17.628 --> 00:29:20.615
but that's a standard
instrument in a jazz quartet,

00:29:20.615 --> 00:29:21.690
jazz ensemble.
 

00:29:21.690 --> 00:29:25.957
But it's a very strong bass and
Baroque music also has a very

00:29:25.957 --> 00:29:29.015
strong bass, so lots of
similarities between

00:29:29.015 --> 00:29:31.858
contemporary jazz and baroque
music.

00:29:31.858 --> 00:29:35.635
And sometimes these jazz
ensembles like to get to this

00:29:35.635 --> 00:29:39.269
Baroque music and resurrect them
in modern idiom.

00:29:39.269 --> 00:29:40.028
All right.
 

00:29:40.028 --> 00:29:44.200
So normally a fugue is a
freestanding piece or you could

00:29:44.200 --> 00:29:47.690
have an entire movement written
as a fugue.

00:29:47.690 --> 00:29:51.433
Haydn--the last movement of the
Haydn quartets will sometimes do

00:29:51.433 --> 00:29:53.693
that,
a Beethoven piano sonata might

00:29:53.693 --> 00:29:55.506
do that,
but usually they're

00:29:55.506 --> 00:29:56.848
freestanding pieces.
 

00:29:56.848 --> 00:29:59.942
Occasionally,
you run into a fugue that's

00:29:59.942 --> 00:30:02.650
embedded inside another
movement.

00:30:02.650 --> 00:30:06.622
You might have a movement in
sonata-allegro form and you get

00:30:06.622 --> 00:30:09.556
to a particular section,
let's say the development

00:30:09.556 --> 00:30:12.367
section, and the composer says,
"Well, I want to write a

00:30:12.367 --> 00:30:14.028
fugue here as my
development."

00:30:14.028 --> 00:30:19.969
When that happens we call it a
fugato, so a fugato is a fugue

00:30:19.969 --> 00:30:22.838
placed inside another form.
 

00:30:22.838 --> 00:30:26.133
So we're going to listen to an
example of this from the

00:30:26.133 --> 00:30:29.670
romantic period in which we have
the young composer Georges

00:30:29.670 --> 00:30:30.278
Bizet.
 

00:30:30.278 --> 00:30:32.539
He was exactly your age when he
wrote this.

00:30:32.539 --> 00:30:34.338
He was nineteen years old.
 

00:30:34.338 --> 00:30:36.788
Georges Bizet wrote this
symphony.

00:30:36.788 --> 00:30:39.116
There's a lovely romantic
string sound,

00:30:39.116 --> 00:30:43.160
sort of break-your-heart string
sound, and then we have a segue.

00:30:43.160 --> 00:30:46.726
We have kind of a romantic
transition here as he changes

00:30:46.726 --> 00:30:50.615
mood and then a fugue will break
out and it will start in the

00:30:50.615 --> 00:30:53.470
bottom voice so I'll tell you
that much.

00:30:53.470 --> 00:30:55.971
And my question to you or my
challenge to you is this:

00:30:55.971 --> 00:30:56.868
What's the order?
 

00:30:56.868 --> 00:30:58.519
Let's say--and I'll tell you
this.

00:30:58.519 --> 00:31:00.838
We've got a four-voice fugue
that's going to start here.

00:31:00.838 --> 00:31:04.279
Can you track the order in
which the voices enter?

00:31:04.279 --> 00:31:05.920
You know we've got the four.
 

00:31:05.920 --> 00:31:07.612
You've got the bass,
tenor, soprano,

00:31:07.612 --> 00:31:08.869
alto--or bass,
tenor, alto,

00:31:08.869 --> 00:31:10.416
soprano, or soprano,
alto, tenor,

00:31:10.416 --> 00:31:10.950
bass.
 

00:31:10.950 --> 00:31:13.140
They can come in any one of
four different--

00:31:13.140 --> 00:31:18.061
well, probably more than four
permutations but the order might

00:31:18.061 --> 00:31:19.828
be alto,
bass, soprano,

00:31:19.828 --> 00:31:22.423
tenor or it might be bass,
alto, tenor,

00:31:22.423 --> 00:31:25.338
soprano or soprano,
alto, tenor and bass.

00:31:25.338 --> 00:31:27.411
We don't know,
and that's your challenge here

00:31:27.411 --> 00:31:29.200
to see if you can track the
subject.

00:31:29.200 --> 00:31:31.509
Here we go.
 

00:31:31.509 --> 00:31:55.309
&gt;
 

00:31:55.309 --> 00:31:57.349
Start.
 

00:31:57.349 --> 00:32:31.868
&gt;
 

00:32:31.868 --> 00:32:32.163
Okay.
 

00:32:32.163 --> 00:32:34.866
We're going to stop it there
just for a minute.

00:32:34.866 --> 00:32:36.630
We're going to pause there.
 

00:32:36.630 --> 00:32:38.410
That's the--all four voices are
in there.

00:32:38.410 --> 00:32:41.430
Could anybody on just one
