00:32:52.700 --> 00:32:53.509
Student:
&gt;

00:32:53.509 --> 00:32:54.084
Prof: Okay.
 

00:32:54.084 --> 00:32:55.650
It started with bass
&gt;

00:32:55.650 --> 00:33:00.231
or maybe even an octave lower.
 

00:33:00.231 --> 00:33:04.509
&gt;
 

00:33:04.509 --> 00:33:07.220
Okay. Then where did he go?
 

00:33:07.220 --> 00:33:08.140
Student: Alto.
 

00:33:08.140 --> 00:33:12.421
Prof: Yeah,
it actually went to the alto

00:33:12.421 --> 00:33:15.119
&gt;
 

00:33:15.119 --> 00:33:16.769
and there--and then where?
 

00:33:16.769 --> 00:33:23.538
Tenor &lt;&lt;plays
piano&gt;&gt;

00:33:23.538 --> 00:33:27.058
and then finally--yeah,
&gt;

00:33:27.058 --> 00:33:29.583
way up high in the first
violins.

00:33:29.583 --> 00:33:31.868
&gt;
 

00:33:31.868 --> 00:33:35.851
And now we're going to get
a--an episode in which he's

00:33:35.851 --> 00:33:39.832
going to play with just a
motive, and then the subject

00:33:39.832 --> 00:33:41.259
will come back.
 

00:33:41.259 --> 00:33:43.038
So here are two questions for
you.

00:33:43.038 --> 00:33:47.046
In which voice is the subject
coming back and what's happened

00:33:47.046 --> 00:33:49.450
to the subject when it comes
back?

00:33:49.450 --> 00:33:50.519
It's changed in one way.
 

00:33:50.519 --> 00:34:03.170
&gt;
 

00:34:03.170 --> 00:34:04.869
Okay. Let's stop it there.
 

00:34:04.869 --> 00:34:06.190
Any takers on that?
 

00:34:06.190 --> 00:34:08.367
And if we were doing a quiz on
