00:34:19.210 --> 00:34:20.090
Student:
&gt;

00:34:20.090 --> 00:34:21.295
Prof: Not bad.
 

00:34:21.295 --> 00:34:24.853
We would take that because it's
kind of high--I'm playing it in

00:34:24.853 --> 00:34:26.460
kind of tenor range here.
 

00:34:26.460 --> 00:34:29.469
I think it was more cellos and
we'd probably--

00:34:29.469 --> 00:34:31.760
with bassoons--and we'd
probably call that bass,

00:34:31.760 --> 00:34:34.052
a bass part,
but fair enough,

00:34:34.052 --> 00:34:39.132
tenor,
and what happened to it?

00:34:39.132 --> 00:34:44.199
&gt;
 

00:34:44.199 --> 00:34:44.755
Roger.
 

00:34:44.755 --> 00:34:45.311
Minor.
 

00:34:45.311 --> 00:34:48.000
&gt;
 

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:51.536
So he modulated to a different
key and then gave you the

00:34:51.536 --> 00:34:55.422
subject in a minor key,
and that's kind of the way

00:34:55.422 --> 00:34:58.809
these fugues operate,
give you an exposition episode

00:34:58.809 --> 00:35:01.547
in which you change key,
bring back the subject in a

00:35:01.547 --> 00:35:02.380
different key.
 

00:35:02.380 --> 00:35:02.983
All right.
 

00:35:02.983 --> 00:35:06.309
So we've now had a fugue from
the nineteenth century,

00:35:06.309 --> 00:35:09.472
although we would call it a
fugato because it's embedded in

00:35:09.472 --> 00:35:12.389
this lovely,
lovely sonata-allegro movement.

00:35:12.389 --> 00:35:14.978
Let's turn to a fugue from the
twentieth century,

00:35:14.978 --> 00:35:18.106
and for this we go to Leonard
Bernstein and you can see the

00:35:18.106 --> 00:35:19.670
playlist up on the board.
 

00:35:19.670 --> 00:35:24.474
New Haven used to be a favorite
try-out city for Broadway

00:35:24.474 --> 00:35:25.420
musicals.
 

00:35:25.420 --> 00:35:28.719
Indeed there was a musical
entitled--it never went

00:35:28.719 --> 00:35:29.460
anywhere.
 

00:35:29.460 --> 00:35:31.762
It was entitled We Bombed in
New Haven,

00:35:31.762 --> 00:35:34.268
meaning that the try-out
&gt;

00:35:34.268 --> 00:35:37.655
of the particular musical was
not a success,

00:35:37.655 --> 00:35:41.119
and where would they try out in
New Haven?

00:35:41.119 --> 00:35:44.445
What was the great theater for
this?

00:35:44.445 --> 00:35:44.920
Hm?
 

00:35:44.920 --> 00:35:45.630
Student: The repertory
theater?

00:35:45.630 --> 00:35:47.159
Prof: The Yale Rep
Theatre?

00:35:47.159 --> 00:35:48.369
Any other takers?
 

00:35:48.369 --> 00:35:50.550
The Shubert Theater.
 

00:35:50.550 --> 00:35:54.005
Yeah, actually in that period
the Yale Rep was actually a

00:35:54.005 --> 00:35:55.920
functioning house of worship.
 

00:35:55.920 --> 00:35:58.599
It was a church at that
--what's now the Yale Rep.

00:35:58.599 --> 00:36:01.708
So is it the Shubert Theater,
which has been here for a long,

00:36:01.708 --> 00:36:02.329
long time?
 

00:36:02.329 --> 00:36:05.670
So Leonard Bernstein came in
here with a show in 1952 called

00:36:05.670 --> 00:36:08.559
Wonderful Town and he
tried it out there,

00:36:08.559 --> 00:36:12.038
and generally speaking it was a
success and he took it down the

00:36:12.038 --> 00:36:13.889
train tracks there to Broadway.
 

00:36:13.889 --> 00:36:17.092
But he took some music out of
it, some music that he thought

00:36:17.092 --> 00:36:20.405
actually was a little bit too
complicated for the choreography

00:36:20.405 --> 00:36:24.092
that he wanted to work into it--
later took that material and

00:36:24.092 --> 00:36:27.621
worked it in to a freestanding
piece called "Prelude,

00:36:27.621 --> 00:36:29.480
Fugue, and Jazz Riff."
 

00:36:29.480 --> 00:36:33.132
So we're going to look at now
just the fugue portion of it

00:36:33.132 --> 00:36:36.210
because it's a very interesting
kind of fugue.

00:36:36.210 --> 00:36:37.940
It's a very complex fugue.
 

00:36:37.940 --> 00:36:40.382
So we're going to start out
here and I'm going to break

00:36:40.382 --> 00:36:40.699
this.
 

00:36:40.699 --> 00:36:43.987
We'll listen,
we'll stop, we'll listen and

00:36:43.987 --> 00:36:48.079
stop so that we can focus on
particular passages.

00:36:48.079 --> 00:36:52.030
So as we start to listen,
see how many voices there are

00:36:52.030 --> 00:36:54.300
in Leonard Bernstein's fugue.
 

00:36:54.300 --> 00:36:56.773
Have a general sense of what
the range is:

00:36:56.773 --> 00:36:58.099
soprano, alto,
bass.

00:36:58.099 --> 00:36:59.018
What else do we need?
 

00:36:59.018 --> 00:36:59.391
Oh, yeah.
 

00:36:59.391 --> 00:37:00.840
What instruments are playing
here?

00:37:00.840 --> 00:37:29.260
&gt;
 

00:37:29.260 --> 00:37:29.628
Okay.
 

00:37:29.628 --> 00:37:33.987
So that's the exposition and a
little bit of the development

00:37:33.987 --> 00:37:36.130
there so what instruments?
 

00:37:36.130 --> 00:37:39.400
Hm? Ducks?
 

00:37:39.400 --> 00:37:39.980
Student: Saxophones?
 

00:37:39.980 --> 00:37:41.119
Prof: Yeah, saxophones.
 

00:37:41.119 --> 00:37:41.402
Yeah.
 

00:37:41.402 --> 00:37:41.686
Okay.
 

00:37:41.686 --> 00:37:44.070
Kneeland said saxophones and
he's right.

00:37:44.070 --> 00:37:45.320
Yeah, so saxophones there.
 

00:37:45.320 --> 00:37:48.168
So we've got--and then
how--roughly how many did you

00:37:48.168 --> 00:37:48.559
hear?
 

00:37:48.559 --> 00:37:51.030
Two, three, four?
 

00:37:51.030 --> 00:37:53.452
Yeah, maybe four,
maybe four different

00:37:53.452 --> 00:37:57.380
saxophones, sort of alto sax,
maybe baritone sax in there.

00:37:57.380 --> 00:38:02.307
And there was one--and so we
are playing this out and it's a

00:38:02.307 --> 00:38:07.070
rather syncopated fugue,
sort of &gt;.

00:38:07.070 --> 00:38:09.460
Let's listen to it again.
 

00:38:09.460 --> 00:38:11.677
No, we don't have time to do
that but here's one thing that

00:38:11.677 --> 00:38:13.170
happened, &lt;&lt;plays
piano&gt;&gt;

00:38:13.170 --> 00:38:15.909
that kind of sound,
&gt;.

00:38:15.909 --> 00:38:19.483
Then after one episode one of
the saxes brought back that

00:38:19.483 --> 00:38:19.994
subject.
 

00:38:19.994 --> 00:38:21.909
&gt;
 

00:38:21.909 --> 00:38:24.875
What's it doing there?
 

00:38:24.875 --> 00:38:28.650
&gt;
 

00:38:28.650 --> 00:38:29.940
What is that?
 

00:38:29.940 --> 00:38:31.239
What's the relationship there?
 

00:38:31.239 --> 00:38:32.018
Student: Is it inverting
it?

00:38:32.018 --> 00:38:34.489
Prof: Yeah,
it's just inverting it.

00:38:34.489 --> 00:38:36.675
It is taking the intervals and
flipping them and that's what

00:38:36.675 --> 00:38:38.010
composers love to do with
fugues,

00:38:38.010 --> 00:38:40.449
and I'll be talking about
interchangeable parts,

00:38:40.449 --> 00:38:44.601
reciprocal relationships with
the mathematical quality of

00:38:44.601 --> 00:38:45.268
fugues.
 

00:38:45.268 --> 00:38:47.070
And so that's what's happening
here.

00:38:47.070 --> 00:38:49.809
We have a moment of melodic
inversion.

00:38:49.809 --> 00:38:52.211
And sometimes in fugues--and
Bach's did this in the musical

00:38:52.211 --> 00:38:54.498
offering--
he can take his fugue subject

00:38:54.498 --> 00:38:58.016
and run it backwards from
beginning to end so they like to

00:38:58.016 --> 00:39:02.150
have these kind of mathematical
permutations of these intervals.

00:39:02.150 --> 00:39:04.630
It's very cerebral stuff,
this fugue business.

00:39:04.630 --> 00:39:09.898
So there we had just a moment
of Leonard Bernstein writing a

00:39:09.898 --> 00:39:12.219
little bit of inversion.
 

00:39:12.219 --> 00:39:15.688
Now what we're about to hear
next is something of a surprise

00:39:15.688 --> 00:39:18.039
because we get a second fugue
subject.

