And it's a different fugue
subject;

00:39:20.349 --> 00:39:22.420
it is not syncopated.
 

00:39:22.420 --> 00:39:27.409
It's rather lyrical,
&gt;

00:39:27.409 --> 00:39:30.940
&gt;
 

00:39:30.940 --> 00:39:32.210
something like that.
 

00:39:32.210 --> 00:39:34.260
So it's nice and lyrical.
 

00:39:34.260 --> 00:39:40.659
And let's listen to how he now
unfolds a second fugue subject.

00:39:40.659 --> 00:39:43.079
So what we have here is called
a double-fugue.

00:39:43.079 --> 00:39:45.860
He's got one exposition with
one fugue subject.

00:39:45.860 --> 00:40:01.114
Now he's going to give us a
completely different exposition

00:40:01.114 --> 00:40:17.949
with yet a second fugue subject,
&gt;

00:40:17.949 --> 00:40:19.295
and then number one comes back.
 

00:40:19.295 --> 00:40:20.599
&gt;
 

00:40:20.599 --> 00:40:20.880
Okay.
 

00:40:20.880 --> 00:40:24.030
We're going to pause it here
because he's now about to do

00:40:24.030 --> 00:40:27.460
something rather interesting
that Bach used to do as well.

00:40:27.460 --> 00:40:30.809
And Bernstein was a consummate
musician, had studied Bach,

00:40:30.809 --> 00:40:33.925
had Bach coming out of his
ears, so he knew about this

00:40:33.925 --> 00:40:35.159
particular trick.
 

00:40:35.159 --> 00:40:36.329
It's called stretto.
 

00:40:36.329 --> 00:40:39.420
You can design a fugue subject,
not only that it could go

00:40:39.420 --> 00:40:42.081
upside down,
but in which the intervals

00:40:42.081 --> 00:40:46.027
instead of coming in long
succession could be piled right

00:40:46.027 --> 00:40:47.789
on top of one another.
 

00:40:47.789 --> 00:40:50.590
So the way he sets this thing
up to begin with is this,

00:40:50.590 --> 00:40:55.257
this, maybe this and then this,
but in the next section it's

00:40:55.257 --> 00:40:59.650
going to go this,
this, this and this.

00:40:59.650 --> 00:41:02.900
The intervals back up on each
other because they have been

00:41:02.900 --> 00:41:06.039
arranged to be consonant at key
points and that's called

00:41:06.039 --> 00:41:08.885
stretto,
Italian word stretto,

00:41:08.885 --> 00:41:11.000
kind of tight--
tight entries here.

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:14.454
So here is fancy little bit of
counterpoint by Leonard

00:41:14.454 --> 00:41:17.650
Bernstein that once again goes
by very quickly.

00:41:17.650 --> 00:41:20.960
&gt;
 

00:41:20.960 --> 00:41:22.590
Do you hear it?
 

00:41:22.590 --> 00:41:34.018
&gt;
 

00:41:34.018 --> 00:41:36.880
Now he's going to bring back
the two subjects together.

00:41:36.880 --> 00:41:42.599
We have one and two together,
&gt;

00:41:42.599 --> 00:41:46.489
episode, &lt;&lt;music
playing&gt;&gt;

00:41:46.489 --> 00:41:50.349
syncopated episode,
&gt;

00:41:50.349 --> 00:41:53.480
one, &lt;&lt;music
playing&gt;&gt;

00:41:53.480 --> 00:41:57.179
two, &lt;&lt;music
playing&gt;&gt;

00:41:57.179 --> 00:41:57.911
and so on.
 

00:41:57.911 --> 00:42:00.110
&gt;
 

00:42:00.110 --> 00:42:03.331
So it's a pretty nifty little
fugue there by Leonard Bernstein

00:42:03.331 --> 00:42:06.130
with lots of intricate
counterpoint involved in it.

00:42:06.130 --> 00:42:07.117
All right.
 

00:42:07.117 --> 00:42:12.751
Let's end now with a fugue of
J.S. Bach and for that we're

00:42:12.751 --> 00:42:18.978
going to turn to an organ fugue
that he wrote about 1710 when he

00:42:18.978 --> 00:42:22.239
was a young man in Weimar.
 

00:42:22.239 --> 00:42:42.289
Here is that fugue subject
&gt;

00:42:42.289 --> 00:42:43.440
and on and on and on it goes.
 

00:42:43.440 --> 00:42:45.989
What's of interest about this
subject?

00:42:45.989 --> 00:42:47.159
Well, two things.
 

00:42:47.159 --> 00:42:50.782
First of all,
as I sing this

00:42:50.782 --> 00:42:53.869
&gt;
 

00:42:53.869 --> 00:42:55.150
what is that?
 

00:42:55.150 --> 00:43:01.320
&gt;
 

00:43:01.320 --> 00:43:04.679
It's an--
Student: Arpeggio.

00:43:04.679 --> 00:43:06.400
Prof: Arpeggio.
 

00:43:06.400 --> 00:43:09.150
Yes, it is, but it's an
arpeggio of what?

00:43:09.150 --> 00:43:11.889
&gt;
 

00:43:11.889 --> 00:43:14.000
&gt;
 

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:18.380
It's a triad,
just a minor triad.

00:43:18.380 --> 00:43:19.811
&gt;
 

00:43:19.811 --> 00:43:23.014
One, five, three,
one, if I skip this note here.

00:43:23.014 --> 00:43:24.650
&gt;
 

00:43:24.650 --> 00:43:27.864
As I come to every strong beat
in this theme,

00:43:27.864 --> 00:43:31.298
every strong beat,
I have a member of the triad,

00:43:31.298 --> 00:43:33.929
that same either G,
B-flat or D.

00:43:33.929 --> 00:43:38.411
So these triads as we said
before are really the structure,

00:43:38.411 --> 00:43:41.659
the backbone,
on which a composer like Bach

00:43:41.659 --> 00:43:45.059
will place the flesh of a fugue
subject.

00:43:45.059 --> 00:43:48.268
So it's very triadic and it
sounds pretty secure for that .

00:43:48.268 --> 00:43:51.152
Now here's another thing that
this fugue subject does and many

00:43:51.152 --> 00:43:52.239
other fugue subjects.
 

00:43:52.239 --> 00:43:54.210
It starts with quarter notes,
&gt;

00:43:54.210 --> 00:43:57.469
quarter, quarter,
quarter, then next measure,

00:43:57.469 --> 00:43:58.961
eighth, eighth,
eighth, eighth,

00:43:58.961 --> 00:44:01.063
eighth,
eighth, and then we get in here

00:44:01.063 --> 00:44:03.735
eighth,
eighth, eighth,

00:44:03.735 --> 00:44:07.119
&gt;.
 

00:44:07.119 --> 00:44:08.719
It's gathering speed.
 

00:44:08.719 --> 00:44:10.440
Of course, the beat isn't going
any faster.

00:44:10.440 --> 00:44:11.920
The tempo is staying the same.
 

00:44:11.920 --> 00:44:14.420
He's simply writing shorter
note values,

00:44:14.420 --> 00:44:16.010
which has the psychological
impact,

00:44:16.010 --> 00:44:18.905
as we've said several times,
of giving the sense of

00:44:18.905 --> 00:44:21.389
movement,
gathering speed here.

00:44:21.389 --> 00:44:23.980
It's like a train pulling out
of the station.

00:44:23.980 --> 00:44:25.420
We want to get on this train.
 

00:44:25.420 --> 00:44:30.112
This thing is really starting
to roll after five measures or

00:44:30.112 --> 00:44:30.510
so.
 

00:44:30.510 --> 00:44:34.693
So it's a pretty nifty fugue
subject here and we're going to

00:44:34.693 --> 00:44:38.166
listen to this now,
and what I'd like to do is the

00:44:38.166 --> 00:44:39.159
following.
 

00:44:39.159 --> 00:44:41.268
We're going to listen to the
entire piece.

00:44:41.268 --> 00:44:51.210
Think about--as the voices come
in, think about where they're

00:44:51.210 --> 00:44:53.199
coming in.
 

00:44:53.199 --> 00:44:57.047
Can you tell me what the
trajectory of the voices is in

00:44:57.047 --> 00:44:58.260
the exposition?
 

00:44:58.260 --> 00:45:00.690
And I'm going to turn out the
lights here because sometimes

00:45:00.690 --> 00:45:03.039
it's good just to kind of go off
into your own world,

00:45:03.039 --> 00:45:05.202
close your eyes,
but I would like you to do the

00:45:05.202 --> 00:45:06.050
following thing.
 

00:45:06.050 --> 00:45:11.860
Kind of lean back,
get comfortable,

00:45:11.860 --> 00:45:19.208
close your eyes,
but every time you hear the

00:45:19.208 --> 00:45:27.239
fugue subject-- &lt;&lt;plays
piano&gt;&gt;

00:45:27.239 --> 00:45:30.885
and so on--every time you hear
that fugue subject raise your

00:45:30.885 --> 00:45:34.038
hand so that I know you're
recognizing that it's the

00:45:34.038 --> 00:45:34.780
subject.
 

00:45:34.780 --> 00:45:37.302
Because listening to fugues,
it's basically one thing:

00:45:37.302 --> 00:45:39.873
Differentiating between a
passage in which you've got a

00:45:39.873 --> 00:45:42.682
statement of the subject and an
episode where there ain't no

00:45:42.682 --> 00:45:44.159
statement of the subject.
 

00:45:44.159 --> 00:45:44.443
Okay.
 

00:45:44.443 --> 00:45:47.748
So this is a three minute and
twenty-second fugue and we're

00:45:47.748 --> 00:45:49.969
going to listen to the whole
thing,

00:45:49.969 --> 00:45:53.081
but do raise your hand when you
think that fugue subject is in

00:45:53.081 --> 00:45:53.489
there.
 

00:45:53.489 --> 00:46:45.239
&gt;
 

00:46:45.239 --> 00:46:49.300
So we've gone soprano,
alto, tenor and now bass.

00:46:49.300 --> 00:47:05.989
&gt;
 

00:47:05.989 --> 00:47:07.650
Yeah, there it is.
 

00:47:07.650 --> 00:47:10.090
It's in one of those inner
voices.

00:47:10.090 --> 00:47:12.860
It's a little bit disguised but
it's in there.

00:47:12.860 --> 00:47:29.230
&gt;
 

00:47:29.230 --> 00:47:36.909
Yep, &lt;&lt;music
playing&gt;&gt;

00:47:36.909 --> 00:47:38.239
inner voice.
 

00:47:38.239 --> 00:47:49.949
&gt;
 

00:47:49.949 --> 00:47:52.420
Yep, way down in the bass.
 

00:47:52.420 --> 00:48:03.900
&gt;
 

00:48:03.900 --> 00:48:08.960
A nice, long sequence here
&gt;

00:48:08.960 --> 00:48:19.150
&gt;
 

00:48:19.150 --> 00:48:23.599
Yep, all the way up on top in
the soprano.

00:48:23.599 --> 00:48:31.699
&gt;
 

00:48:31.699 --> 00:48:36.650
Another episode,
descending sequence this time.

00:48:36.650 --> 00:48:44.349
&gt;
 

00:48:44.349 --> 00:48:48.030
Rising sequences here,
&gt;

00:48:48.030 --> 00:48:54.530
falling sequences &lt;&lt;music
playing&gt;&gt;

00:48:54.530 --> 00:48:58.170
in the bass.
 

00:48:58.170 --> 00:49:12.460
&gt;
 

00:49:12.460 --> 00:49:15.228
Okay, so that's a wonderful
fugue by J.S. Bach and we

00:49:15.228 --> 00:49:18.369
could--we're going to talk more
about this in section,

00:49:18.369 --> 00:49:21.534
this idea how you can run your
fugue parts this way or you

00:49:21.534 --> 00:49:23.090
could order them this way.
 

00:49:23.090 --> 00:49:25.856
You can think of these
constructs mathematically or you

00:49:25.856 --> 00:49:28.878
can think of them musically,
but you're all working with the

00:49:28.878 --> 00:49:30.210
same kind of material.
 

00:49:30.210 --> 00:49:33.257
As you go out,
one final fugue by Glenn Gould

00:49:33.257 --> 00:49:37.342
who is going to teach you how to
write a fugue as he sings a

00:49:37.342 --> 00:49:38.519
fugue to you.
 

00:49:38.519 --> 00:49:56.739
&gt;
 

00:49:56.739 --> 00:50:02.000
 
 

